or Independence.* \r\n\r\n\u201cAs I believe the voice of my constituents and all sensible and honest men is in favor of Independence, and as my own judgment concurs with them, I give my vote for Independence.\u201d\r\n\r\nThat single vote - broke the tie - and Initiated, officially, the American Revolution and Birthed The United States of America. ", "author": "Bullet3250", "created": 1783172449809, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Bullet3250", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "Philedelphia, PA. July 2, 1776...   The Vote for Independence in the Continental Congress is - 'TIED' ... some members think it too soon... others desire to remain under the King...others know well, that voting in the affirmative for Independence... is clearlyTreason for which the penalty is death. ", "last_comment_created": 1783176808752, "content": "<p>Enter the hero of the story, <strong>Caesar Rodney, from Delaware</strong>.</p>\n<p>He is currently in Delaware, and was absent during the voting for Independence due to illness. He received word of the deadlock in voting and wasted no time. Caesar Rodney, an asthmatic, ill and suffering, mounted his horse - rode 80 miles in 18 hrs. straight. His sight-impaired, this American hero rides through a thunderstorm, with a scarf around his face to hide the cancerous tumor in his eye. <em>He walks in to the Continental Congress, and casts the deciding vote for Independence.</em></p>\n<p>\u201cAs I believe the voice of my constituents and all sensible and honest men is in favor of Independence, and as my own judgment concurs with them, I give my vote for Independence.\u201d</p>\n<p>That single vote - broke the tie - and Initiated, officially, the American 